// Pilot claim suite for the claim-grounding eval (docs/plans/claim-grounding-eval.md).
// 61 items over the 3 pilot papers: Bewley2016 (SORT), Caesar2020 (nuScenes),
// Liang2020 (LaneGCN). Every evidence span is quoted from the ORIGINAL PDF,
// never the markdown, so the mode-1 vs mode-2 gap is not contaminated.
//
// Schema: { id, paper, category, claim, verdict, evidence?, page? }. `paper` is
// the paper SERVED to modes 1-2 (the containing paper for single-paper claims;
// a pre-registered decoy for the not-supported family). Verdict is the primary
// grade; evidence is advisory.
//
// Labeling policy (docs/plans/claim-grounding-eval.md, "Labeling policy"):
//   supported    - the paper states the claim.
//   refuted      - the paper fills a single-valued slot (architecture, benchmark,
//                  metric, reported value) differently => the claim is false from
//                  this paper alone. Category `contradicted` for the decoy-served
//                  version of this.
//   not-found    - the claim is additive to what the paper describes and the
//                  paper is silent. Category `not-addressed`: the pure
//                  hallucination probe. The headline metric here is
//                  false-supported rate, not exact not-found/refuted match.
//
// STATUS: drafted and self-checked against the PDF, NOT yet independently
// human-verified. Verify before any scored run counts these numbers.
//
// --- Bewley2016 (SORT): clean-prose control -------------------------------
{"id":"bew-1","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"verbatim","claim":"SORT updates at a rate of 260 Hz.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"the tracker updates at a rate of 260 Hz which is over 20x faster than other state-of-the-art trackers","page":1}
{"id":"bew-2","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"numeric","claim":"Changing the detector can improve tracking performance by up to 18.9%.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"changing the detector can improve tracking by up to 18.9%","page":1}
{"id":"bew-3","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"paraphrase","claim":"SORT combines a Kalman filter with the Hungarian algorithm for its tracking components.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"a rudimentary combination of familiar techniques such as the Kalman Filter and Hungarian algorithm for the tracking components","page":1}
{"id":"bew-4","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"paraphrase","claim":"SORT uses appearance features for data association.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"appearance features beyond the detection component are ignored and only the bounding box position and size are used for both motion estimation and data association","page":1}
{"id":"bew-5","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"paraphrase","claim":"SORT approximates each object's inter-frame displacement with a linear constant velocity model independent of other objects and camera motion.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"We approximate the inter-frame displacements of each object with a linear constant velocity model which is independent of other objects and camera motion","page":2}
{"id":"bew-6","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"verbatim","claim":"SORT solves the detection-to-target assignment optimally using the Hungarian algorithm.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"The assignment is solved optimally using the Hungarian algorithm","page":2}
{"id":"bew-7","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"numeric","claim":"SORT passes only person detections with output probability greater than 50% to the tracker.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"we ignore all other classes and only pass person detection results with output probabilities greater than 50% to the tracking framework","page":2}
{"id":"bew-8","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"paraphrase","claim":"SORT uses the Faster R-CNN framework for its detection component.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"we utilise the Faster Region CNN (FrRCNN) detection framework","page":2}
{"id":"bew-9","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"numeric-table","claim":"With the FrRCNN(VGG16) detector, the proposed method reaches a MOTA of 34.0 on the validation sequences.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"Proposed FrRCNN(VGG16) 49.5 77.5 274 34.0","page":3}
{"id":"bew-10","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"numeric-table","claim":"The proposed method achieves higher tracking accuracy (MOTA) with the ACF detector than with FrRCNN(VGG16).","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"Proposed ACF 33.6 65.7 224 15.1 ... FrRCNN(VGG16) 49.5 77.5 274 34.0","page":3}
{"id":"bew-11","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"paraphrase","claim":"When no detection is associated to a target, SORT predicts its state without correction using the linear velocity model.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"If no detection is associated to the target, its state is simply predicted without correction","page":2}
{"id":"bew-12","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"numeric","claim":"SORT sets the TLost parameter to 1 in all experiments.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"In all experiments TLost is set to 1","page":2}
{"id":"bew-13","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"figure-dependent","claim":"In the paper's accuracy-versus-speed figure, the proposed method (SORT) sits above the realtime threshold line.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"Benchmark performance of the proposed method (SORT) in relation to several baseline trackers","page":1}
{"id":"bew-14","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"paraphrase","claim":"SORT targets online tracking, using only detections from the previous and current frame.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"primarily targeted towards online tracking where only detections from the previous and the current frame are presented to the tracker","page":1}
{"id":"bew-15","paper":"Bewley2016","category":"numeric","claim":"SORT's tracking component runs at 26 Hz on a single core.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"tracking component runs at 260 Hz on single core of an Intel","page":5}
// --- Caesar2020 (nuScenes): table-dense -----------------------------------
{"id":"cae-1","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"verbatim","claim":"nuScenes comprises 1000 scenes, each 20 seconds long.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"nuScenes comprises 1000 scenes, each 20s long and fully annotated with 3D bounding boxes for 23 classes and 8 attributes","page":1}
{"id":"cae-2","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric","claim":"nuScenes has 100 times as many images as the KITTI dataset.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"It has 7x as many annotations and 100x as many images as the pioneering KITTI dataset","page":1}
{"id":"cae-3","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"nuScenes annotates 3D bounding boxes for 23 classes and 8 attributes.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"fully annotated with 3D bounding boxes for 23 classes and 8 attributes","page":1}
{"id":"cae-4","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"nuScenes annotates 3D bounding boxes for 40 object classes.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"fully annotated with 3D bounding boxes for 23 classes and 8 attributes","page":1}
{"id":"cae-5","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"The nuScenes sensor suite has 6 cameras, 5 radars, and 1 lidar with full 360-degree coverage.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"6 cameras, 5 radars and 1 lidar, all with full 360 degree field of view","page":1}
{"id":"cae-6","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"not-addressed","claim":"nuScenes provides annotations for pedestrian gaze direction.","verdict":"not-found","page":1}
{"id":"cae-7","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric","claim":"nuScenes annotates keyframes at 2 Hz.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"We annotate the object classes in every keyframe","page":4}
{"id":"cae-8","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"The nuScenes lidar is a spinning sensor with 32 beams capturing at 20 Hz.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"1x Lidar Spinning, 32 beams, 20Hz capture frequency, 360","page":3}
{"id":"cae-9","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"The nuScenes lidar uses 64 beams.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"1x Lidar Spinning, 32 beams, 20Hz capture frequency, 360","page":3}
{"id":"cae-10","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"nuScenes data was collected by driving in Boston and Singapore.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"We drive in Boston (Seaport and South Boston) and Singapore (One North, Holland Village and","page":4}
{"id":"cae-11","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric","claim":"On average, each nuScenes keyframe contains 7 pedestrians and 20 vehicles.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"Per keyframe there are 7 pedestrians and 20 vehicles on average","page":5}
{"id":"cae-12","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"The nuScenes detection metric matches predictions to ground truth by 2D center distance rather than intersection-over-union.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"our proposed 2m center-distance matching versus the IOU","page":6}
{"id":"cae-13","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"The nuScenes detection metric matches predictions to ground truth using bounding-box intersection-over-union.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"our proposed 2m center-distance matching versus the IOU","page":6}
{"id":"cae-14","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric","claim":"The nuScenes lidar produces up to 1.4 million points per second.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"up to 1.4M points per second","page":3}
{"id":"cae-15","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"numeric","claim":"In nuScenes the cameras run at 20 Hz.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"The cameras run at 12Hz while the lidar runs at 20Hz","page":3}
{"id":"cae-16","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"figure-dependent","claim":"The example scene figure shows six camera views together with lidar and radar data and a human-annotated semantic map.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"We see 6 different camera views, lidar and radar data, as well as the human annotated semantic map","page":1}
{"id":"cae-17","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"not-addressed","claim":"nuScenes includes synchronized audio recordings captured from the vehicle.","verdict":"not-found","page":1}
{"id":"cae-18","paper":"Caesar2020","category":"not-addressed","claim":"nuScenes annotates the signal state of every traffic light in each keyframe.","verdict":"not-found","page":1}
// --- Liang2020 (LaneGCN): worst-case (equations, grouped tables, figures) --
{"id":"lia-1","paper":"Liang2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"LaneGCN constructs a lane graph from raw map data instead of rasterizing the map into image-like inputs.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"Instead of encoding vectorized maps as raster images, we construct a lane graph from raw map data to explicitly preserve the map structure","page":1}
{"id":"lia-2","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"On Argoverse, LaneGCN (Our Model) achieves a minADE of 0.87 at K=6.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"Our Model 1.71 3.78 0.59 0.87 1.36 0.16","page":11}
{"id":"lia-3","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"On Argoverse, LaneGCN achieves a minADE of 1.71 at K=6.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"Our Model 1.71 3.78 0.59 0.87 1.36 0.16","page":11}
{"id":"lia-4","paper":"Liang2020","category":"equation","claim":"For regression, LaneGCN applies the smooth L1 loss on all predicted time steps.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"For regression, we apply the smooth l1 loss on all predicted time steps","page":10}
{"id":"lia-5","paper":"Liang2020","category":"equation","claim":"LaneGCN uses a max-margin loss for classification.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"For classification, we use the max-margin loss","page":10}
{"id":"lia-6","paper":"Liang2020","category":"contradicted","claim":"LaneGCN reports its main results on the nuScenes prediction benchmark.","verdict":"refuted","page":1,"evidence":"our approach significantly outperforms the state-of-the-art on the large scale Argoverse motion forecasting benchmark"}
{"id":"lia-7","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"LaneGCN's fusion network models four types of interactions.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"four types of interactions: actor-to-lane, lane-to-lane, lane-to-actor and actor-to-actor","page":1}
{"id":"lia-8","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"LaneGCN's fusion network models three types of interactions.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"four types of interactions: actor-to-lane, lane-to-lane, lane-to-actor and actor-to-actor","page":1}
{"id":"lia-9","paper":"Liang2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"LaneGCN uses a 1D CNN to extract features from the actors' past trajectories.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"here we use an 1D CNN to process the trajectory input for its effectiveness in extracting multi-scale features","page":6}
{"id":"lia-10","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric","claim":"On Argoverse, models predict a 3-second future horizon.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"predict the future locations of agents in a 3 seconds future horizon","page":11}
{"id":"lia-11","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric","claim":"On Argoverse, models predict a 5-second future horizon.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"predict the future locations of agents in a 3 seconds future horizon","page":11}
{"id":"lia-12","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"The Argoverse training split contains 205942 sequences.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"205942, 39472 and 78143 sequences","page":11}
{"id":"lia-13","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric","claim":"For the Argoverse test set, only the first 2 seconds of each sequence are provided.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"For the test set, only the first 2 seconds are provided","page":11}
{"id":"lia-14","paper":"Liang2020","category":"equation","claim":"LaneGCN's max-margin classification loss uses a margin of 1.0.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"L = Lcls + a*Lreg, where a = 1.0 (the regression loss weight); in the max-margin loss the margin is a separate parameter epsilon","page":10}
{"id":"lia-15","paper":"Liang2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"Unlike VectorNet, LaneGCN uses polyline segments as map nodes rather than polyline-level nodes.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"VectorNet uses polyline-level nodes for interaction, while our LaneGCN uses polyline segments as map nodes","page":3}
{"id":"lia-16","paper":"Liang2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"LaneGCN extends graph convolutions with multiple adjacency matrices and along-lane dilation.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"extends graph convolutions with multiple adjacency matrices and along-lane dilation","page":1}
{"id":"lia-17","paper":"Liang2020","category":"figure-dependent","claim":"In LaneGCN's approach figure, ActorNet and LaneGCN produce features that feed a FusionNet outputting the future predictions.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"We construct a lane graph from raw map data and use LaneGCN to extract map features. In parallel, ActorNet extracts actor features","page":2}
{"id":"lia-18","paper":"Liang2020","category":"paraphrase","claim":"LaneGCN represents both actors and lanes as nodes in a graph.","verdict":"supported","evidence":"we represent both actors and lanes as nodes in the graph","page":2}
{"id":"lia-19","paper":"Liang2020","category":"contradicted","claim":"LaneGCN incorporates traffic light state as an input feature.","verdict":"refuted","page":1,"evidence":"we represent both actors and lanes as nodes in the graph"}
{"id":"lia-20","paper":"Liang2020","category":"numeric-table","claim":"On Argoverse, LaneGCN (Our Model) achieves a minADE of 0.87 at K=1.","verdict":"refuted","evidence":"Our Model 1.71 3.78 0.59 0.87 1.36 0.16","page":11}
